    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-09-17T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-09-17T07:00:00-05:00" n="366"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d366">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/24314: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Algiers (<persName type="from"
                            >Cole</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Algiers</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-09-17T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >September 17, 1942—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 2:37 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>610. I learn from a well-informed military source here that high military circles
                    are very apprehensive that following the occupation of Madagascar<note n="54"
                        xml:id="d366fn54">Occupied by British forces beginning May 4, 1942; for
                        correspondence, see <ref target="#pg_687">pp. 687</ref> ff.</note> the
                    Germans may bring pressure on Vichy to admit them to a share at least of the
                    defense of the French Empire particularly North Africa and Dakar because, the
                    Germans are expected to say, you have proved yourself incapable of defending
                    it.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Vichy and Casablanca, true reading to Tunis.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cole</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
